47
00:08:49,940 --> 00:09:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, ladies and gentlemen, it is a great pleasure to be in Zakareb today and to have the opportunity to share with you some thoughts on financial stability in Europe and, in particular, how to improve it.

48
00:09:02,940 --> 00:09:11,940
[SPEAKER_00] Financial stability is a critical condition for achieving our common goals of prosperity and sustainable growth.

49
00:09:11,940 --> 00:09:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] Yet, the financial landscape on which both regulators and market participants operate has been rapidly changing.

50
00:09:21,940 --> 00:09:30,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is very difficult today, very different today from what it was only ten years ago, and it will be very different ten years from now.

51
00:09:30,940 --> 00:09:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] I will begin by describing the present landscape on which efforts to strengthen financial stability have been taking place.

52
00:09:41,940 --> 00:09:51,940
[SPEAKER_00] Then, I will briefly discuss some developments in the European Union regulatory framework relevant to the financial system and its stability.

53
00:09:51,940 --> 00:10:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] In particular, we can identify a new role for central banks in this framework that stems from mandates that have been revised to include the safeguarding of financial stability.

54
00:10:04,940 --> 00:10:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] I conclude by outlining the challenges ahead and I provide some thoughts on the way forward.

55
00:10:12,940 --> 00:10:16,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, what is the setting? What is the broader context?

56
00:10:16,940 --> 00:10:33,940
[SPEAKER_00] Beginning with the initial efforts to forge closer European integration in the early 50s, the European Union has faced a series of challenges that have, at times, tested both the coherence and the stability of the Union.

57
00:10:33,940 --> 00:10:47,940
[SPEAKER_00] The responses to these challenges have shown that the European Union is built on solid ground, as the bonds among member states have become stronger ever since.

58
00:10:47,940 --> 00:10:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] To cite two notable examples:

59
00:10:49,940 --> 00:11:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] The breakdown of the Bretton Woods system in the early 70s led to the creation of the European monetary system, or EMS, in the late 70s.

60
00:11:01,940 --> 00:11:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] Then, the breakdown of the EMS in the early 90s led to the creation of the Euro in 1999.

61
00:11:08,940 --> 00:11:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] The developments since the eruption of the 2007-2008 international financial crisis have further strengthened the bonds among European Union members.

62
00:11:22,940 --> 00:11:30,940
[SPEAKER_00] That crisis raised issues related to too big to fail, too big to save, and too complex to resolve.

63
00:11:30,940 --> 00:11:44,940
[SPEAKER_00] The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision following the G20 agreement in 2008 took on the task of comprehensively strengthening international bank regulatory standards.

64
00:11:45,940 --> 00:12:03,940
[SPEAKER_00] It's updated report, presented to G20 leaders last November, noted that substantial progress has been made towards finalizing post-crisis reforms and that the regulatory reform agenda for global banks has almost been completed.

65
00:12:04,940 --> 00:12:17,940
[SPEAKER_00] Further clarification of these elements will provide regulatory clarity, certainty, and supporting the banking sector's ability to make long-term sustainable business plans.

66
00:12:18,940 --> 00:12:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] The Euro-area financial crisis, which originated in 2009-2010, provided another, more serious challenge to the stability of the European Union.

67
00:12:30,940 --> 00:12:45,940
[SPEAKER_00] More recently, with the recovery in the Euro-area still fragile, a slowdown in growth in the emerging market economies, along with a rise in geopolitical tensions, which have led to an unprecedented refugee crisis.

68
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] And the concerns about the Brexit have led to an increase in uncertainty.

69
00:12:50,940 --> 00:13:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] Finally, different approaches among member states regarding banking union, and the slow progress in establishing a single European deposit insurance scheme, have been hindering further progress in securing the financial system architecture needed to enhance stability.

70
00:13:09,940 --> 00:13:28,940
[SPEAKER_00] A salient characteristic, since the onset of the Euro-area crisis, is that stock market shares of European banks have been trading at a discount to tangible book value, while those of the largest U.S. banks have traded at a premium to book value.

71
00:13:29,940 --> 00:13:47,940
[SPEAKER_00] The situation cannot anymore be explained by differences in capital adequacy ratios, since capital ratios for Euro-area banks have risen substantially from about 8% in 2008 to about 14% expected this year, 2016.

72
00:13:48,940 --> 00:14:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] On the contrary, these differences are indicative of a European banking sector undergoing a transformation that demands a comprehensive and radical adjustment of the core business model of operation.

73
00:14:00,940 --> 00:14:14,940
[SPEAKER_00] The first two months of 2016 show a sharp deterioration in market sentiment, related to not only a weakening of global economic activity, but also other concerns.

74
00:14:15,940 --> 00:14:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] First, the threat of low nominal growth, generating not only high non-performing loans, that is the NPL ratios, but also lower and flatter yield curves, with potential negative effects on banks' profitability.

75
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] Second, concerns about the effectiveness of monetary policy, with some market analysts believing that central banks may be running out of ammunition.

76
00:14:44,940 --> 00:14:46,940
[SPEAKER_00] I can assure you that they are not.

77
00:14:46,940 --> 00:14:54,940
[SPEAKER_00] The monetary policy decisions by the ECB's governing council two weeks ago, provide a very clear confirmation of this fact.

78
00:14:54,940 --> 00:15:10,940
[SPEAKER_00] Third, regulatory uncertainty about the suite of capital and bail-in requirements, the supervisory review and examination process, the SREP, sorry about the acronyms, but from now on you have to be used to them.

79
00:15:11,940 --> 00:15:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] The minimum requirement for own funds and eligible liabilities, MRL, the total loss absorption capacity, TLAQ, and EBA guidance on the minimum distributable amount, MDA.

80
00:15:25,940 --> 00:15:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] The uncertainty as to the actual effects that can be expected from the newly introduced BRRD instruments seems to have played a role.

81
00:15:32,940 --> 00:15:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] Fourth, negative feedback loops between equity and debt markets, amplified by low secondary market liquidity.

82
00:15:42,940 --> 00:15:48,940
[SPEAKER_00] That was the COCOS market that experienced a large increase in yields recently.

83
00:15:48,940 --> 00:15:52,940
[SPEAKER_00] What has been now the European Union response?

84
00:15:52,940 --> 00:16:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, the responses of the European Union to the weaknesses to the financial stability landscape that emerged have been actually very effective.

85
00:16:05,940 --> 00:16:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] despite the initial lack of crisis mechanisms and the unfavorable and challenging environment, an environment in which many fires were often being simultaneously fought on a number of fronts.

86
00:16:22,940 --> 00:16:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] Initially, the response came in the form of monetary policy and the significant easing of the monetary policy stamps.

87
00:16:29,940 --> 00:16:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] Indeed, in October 2008, six major central banks, including the European Central Bank, executed a coordinated and simultaneous cut in the interest rates.

88
00:16:42,940 --> 00:16:55,940
[SPEAKER_00] Additionally, at that time, the Euro-area countries set out an action plan of coordinated measures to restore confidence and improve financing conditions in the economy.

89
00:16:55,940 --> 00:17:03,940
[SPEAKER_00] These measures included the granting of government guarantees on bank debt issuance and the recapitalization of banks.

90
00:17:04,940 --> 00:17:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] With the eruption of the Euro-area financial crisis in 2010, and during subsequent periods, when the monetary transmission mechanism was dysfunctional,

91
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] the ECB increasingly implemented non-standard monetary tools.

92
00:17:20,940 --> 00:17:26,940
[SPEAKER_00] Additionally, to provide financial assistance to countries under stress,

93
00:17:27,940 --> 00:17:35,940
[SPEAKER_00] in 2010, in 2010, the Europe created the EFSF, which was replaced by the ESM in October 2012.

94
00:17:35,940 --> 00:17:46,940
[SPEAKER_00] Perhaps the greatest challenge and a surprise posed by the Euro-area crisis was in the area of financial integration and banking.

95
00:17:47,940 --> 00:17:55,940
[SPEAKER_00] At the inception of the Euro, it was widely expected, not only by economists but also by market practitioners,

96
00:17:55,940 --> 00:18:01,940
[SPEAKER_00] that the single currency would spur integration across previously fragmented European financial markets.

97
00:18:01,940 --> 00:18:06,940
[SPEAKER_00] Economists believed that this integration would be stabilizing.

98
00:18:07,940 --> 00:18:17,940
[SPEAKER_00] The portfolio diversification and access to credit markets were expected to encourage risk sharing, while making national demand less dependent on national income.

99
00:18:17,940 --> 00:18:23,940
[SPEAKER_00] That is, portfolio diversification was expected to encourage consumption smoothing.

100
00:18:23,940 --> 00:18:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] And for the Euro's first ten years, that scenario unfolded very much as expected.

101
00:18:30,940 --> 00:18:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] Then came a major surprise.

102
00:18:32,940 --> 00:18:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] The Euro-area crisis revealed that countries within a monetary union can become subject to balance of payment crisis.

103
00:18:40,940 --> 00:18:48,940
[SPEAKER_00] A possibility that had been almost completely overlooked by economists and by the architects of the Euro.

104
00:18:48,940 --> 00:18:55,940
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, once a crisis erupted, whether in the sovereign sector or the banking sector,

105
00:18:56,940 --> 00:19:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] the central feature of the crisis was the negative feedback loops between banking fragility and sovereign weakness.

106
00:19:04,940 --> 00:19:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] One factor contributing to those feedback loops was the following:

107
00:19:09,940 --> 00:19:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] Although the largest banks in the Euro-area and the United States are of roughly the same size in terms of Euro-area GDP and US GDP respectively,

108
00:19:21,940 --> 00:19:31,940
[SPEAKER_00] the largest Euro-area banks represent a much larger share of any individual national economy in the Euro-area compared with the situation of US banks.

109
00:19:31,940 --> 00:19:42,940
[SPEAKER_00] This circumstance implies that the fiscal consequences of Euro-area bank failures could be large enough to bring state solvency into question.

110
00:19:43,940 --> 00:19:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, the fact that the bank regulation and supervision prior to the crisis were mostly national,

111
00:19:50,940 --> 00:19:56,940
[SPEAKER_00] was seen as having contributed to the crisis and as having impeded its effective resolution.

112
00:19:56,940 --> 00:20:05,940
[SPEAKER_00] Consequently, a key lesson of that crisis has been that a monetary union is not viable in the absence of a banking union.

113
00:20:06,940 --> 00:20:16,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, in response to these developments, in 2012, European leaders initiated the creation of the banking union,

114
00:20:16,940 --> 00:20:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] which is an integral part of a genuine economic and financial union in Europe.

115
00:20:22,940 --> 00:20:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] The three pillars of the banking union are:

116
00:20:24,940 --> 00:20:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] The single supervisory mechanism, the single resolution mechanism, and the still-to-be-completed common deposit guarantee scheme.

117
00:20:32,940 --> 00:20:45,940
[SPEAKER_00] As of January 1, 2016, the Banking Recovery and Resolution Directive, the BRRD, which sets common EU rules for failing banks, entered into full force.

118
00:20:46,940 --> 00:21:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] The BRRD aims, inter-allia, to end the policy of bailing out failing banks by introducing bail-in tools to ensure that losses are borne by creditors, including senior unsecured creditors.

119
00:21:00,940 --> 00:21:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] The BRRD, especially its bail-in tool, has been criticized, perhaps with some justification.

120
00:21:09,940 --> 00:21:19,940
[SPEAKER_00] However, the argument sometimes made, namely that the activation of the BRRD has been a primary cause of the recent deterioration in market sentiment,

121
00:21:19,940 --> 00:21:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] including the large losses in European bank stocks, is rather far-fetched.

122
00:21:24,940 --> 00:21:30,940
[SPEAKER_00] The provisions of the BRRD have been widely known since 2014.

123
00:21:31,940 --> 00:21:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] What analysts, perhaps, fail to realize is that the new and stricter rules introduced with the BRRD will affect the volatility of the prices of bank shares,

124
00:21:43,940 --> 00:21:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] should concerns be raised about the bank's profitability, solvency, and most importantly, their viability.

125
00:21:50,940 --> 00:21:59,940
[SPEAKER_00] That said, we must keep in mind that the BRRD is a new and untested framework for failing banks,

126
00:21:59,940 --> 00:22:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] and it is not particularly suited to addressing a systemic crisis.

127
00:22:05,940 --> 00:22:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] It will be revised by June 2018.

128
00:22:09,940 --> 00:22:19,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, we will have to closely monitor its implementation and identify any areas where adjustments and fine-tuning will be needed.

129
00:22:19,940 --> 00:22:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] While we may need tools for failing banks, our primary aim as supervisors is the prevention of bank failure,

130
00:22:30,940 --> 00:22:35,940
[SPEAKER_00] in order to foster financial stability and ensure that depositors remain protected.

131
00:22:35,940 --> 00:22:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] As John Vickers recently highlighted, orderly bank failure is better than disorderly failure,

132
00:22:43,940 --> 00:22:47,940
[SPEAKER_00] but it is best not to fail in the first place.

133
00:22:47,940 --> 00:22:52,940
[SPEAKER_00] Regulators are adding usefully to the supply of fire extinguishers.

134
00:22:52,940 --> 00:22:59,940
[SPEAKER_00] With more fire extinguishers, the average damage from a fire is materially reduced.

135
00:23:00,940 --> 00:23:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] But that is no good reason to economize on fire prevention.

136
00:23:04,940 --> 00:23:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, let me now turn to the issue of crisis prevention.

137
00:23:09,940 --> 00:23:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] The challenges facing European Union financial sectors in recent years have significantly increased the responsibilities of central banks in the area of crisis prevention.

138
00:23:22,940 --> 00:23:27,940
[SPEAKER_00] The mandates have been amended to explicitly refer to financial stability,

139
00:23:27,940 --> 00:23:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] typically defined as avoiding rapid credit growth combined with increases in asset prices beyond those justified by the economic fundamentals as a core central bank task.

140
00:23:42,940 --> 00:23:56,940
[SPEAKER_00] The toolbox for providing financial stability has been expanded to include macro prudential policy tools and enhanced micro prudential policy tools for both the national authorities and the SSM.

141
00:23:57,940 --> 00:24:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] Examples of macro prudential tools include a counter cyclical capital buffer, a systemic risk buffer and the other systemically important institutions buffer,

142
00:24:08,940 --> 00:24:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] along with measures to control inter-allia, leverage, liquidity and large exposures.

143
00:24:16,940 --> 00:24:23,940
[SPEAKER_00] In the past, it was not thought to be necessary to separate monetary policy from the task of providing financial stability.

144
00:24:23,940 --> 00:24:34,940
[SPEAKER_00] It was thought that price stability in the market for goods and services would be sufficient to ensure financial stability in the market for assets.

145
00:24:35,940 --> 00:24:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] The experience since the early 2000s has dispelled such beliefs.

146
00:24:40,940 --> 00:24:48,940
[SPEAKER_00] That experience has shown that the business cycle and the financial cycle are not necessarily synchronized.

147
00:24:48,940 --> 00:24:54,940
[SPEAKER_00] Long periods of disconnect between the two cycles can actually materialize.

148
00:24:54,940 --> 00:25:03,940
[SPEAKER_00] In particular, the financial cycle tends to have larger amplitude and lower frequency than the normal business cycle.

149
00:25:04,940 --> 00:25:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] The macro prudential policy bridges the gap between the micro prudential supervision of individual banks and monetary policy.

150
00:25:12,940 --> 00:25:23,940
[SPEAKER_00] Its objectives are, first, to enhance the resilience of financial institutions and the entire financial system, and second, to smooth the financial cycle.

151
00:25:23,940 --> 00:25:33,940
[SPEAKER_00] In this regard, macro prudential policy allows monetary policy to focus on maintaining price stability so that real economy activity can flourish.

152
00:25:34,940 --> 00:25:39,940
[SPEAKER_00] While micro prudential supervision focuses on individual institutions.

153
00:25:39,940 --> 00:25:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] In this way, macro prudential policy enhances the institutional separation that is one of the principles of the architecture of the euro area.

154
00:25:50,940 --> 00:26:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] Indeed, I believe that a strong case can be made that had macro prudential tools been available ten years ago, we may not have had a euro area crisis.

155
00:26:03,940 --> 00:26:17,940
[SPEAKER_00] Ten years ago, macro prudential tools to limit the excess borrowing that was taking place in the soon-to-be crisis countries were either not used or were too weak to dampen credit growth efficiently in those countries.

156
00:26:18,940 --> 00:26:34,940
[SPEAKER_00] That said, the usefulness of coordinating policies should not be forgotten, whether that be coordination of specific policies across different countries, as happened in the wake of the failure of Lehman Brothers with the simultaneous cuts in policy rates,

157
00:26:35,940 --> 00:26:36,940
[SPEAKER_00] to ensure coordination of those countries.

158
00:26:36,940 --> 00:26:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] The respect for the independence of the various authorities involved in securing financial stability should not imply separation and a lack of coordination.

159
00:26:51,940 --> 00:27:01,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, I strongly agree with Daniel Nui that micro prudential supervision needs to be complemented by a macro prudential perspective.

160
00:27:01,940 --> 00:27:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is imperative, however, that the macro prudential toolbox be further enhanced with innovative tools beyond those focused on capital requirements.

161
00:27:12,940 --> 00:27:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] Cyclical systemic risk can arise not only as a result of excessive credit expansion, an issue that now can be addressed with a counter-cyclical capital buffer,

162
00:27:24,940 --> 00:27:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] but also because of inadequate channeling of credit that keeps the real economy under-financed for extended periods.

163
00:27:33,940 --> 00:27:42,940
[SPEAKER_00] A lesson drawn from the crisis is that we have focused on rather narrow areas of financial activity.

164
00:27:42,940 --> 00:27:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] Nowadays, it is important that we focus on the risks that might be missed at the micro level,

165
00:27:49,940 --> 00:27:53,940
[SPEAKER_00] that is the interlinkages between and among sectors,

166
00:27:53,940 --> 00:27:59,940
[SPEAKER_00] and thus explore how the financial system can influence and be influenced by the wider economy.

167
00:28:00,940 --> 00:28:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] That is, we need a general equilibrium approach.

168
00:28:02,940 --> 00:28:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] In the Euro area, there is evidence of limited financing of the real economy,

169
00:28:08,940 --> 00:28:14,940
[SPEAKER_00] with the consequence that Euro area investment has not recovered to pre-2008 levels,

170
00:28:14,940 --> 00:28:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] despite ECB policies directly aimed at increasing the lending of the banking sector.

171
00:28:25,940 --> 00:28:28,940
[SPEAKER_00] Apart from the elements of banking union and the BRRD,

172
00:28:28,940 --> 00:28:33,940
[SPEAKER_00] a number of other important regulatory initiatives have been taken,

173
00:28:33,940 --> 00:28:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] covering not only the banking sector, but also insurance, financial markets and infrastructures.

174
00:28:40,940 --> 00:28:46,940
[SPEAKER_00] Many initiatives are ongoing, and further steps are required for their completion.

175
00:28:47,940 --> 00:28:52,940
[SPEAKER_00] If macro-prudential policy is to effectively curb the financial cycle,

176
00:28:52,940 --> 00:28:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] it is essential to have tools that deal with the credit-real estate relationship.

177
00:28:57,940 --> 00:29:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] There are two ways to deal with this relationship.

178
00:29:02,940 --> 00:29:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] The first is by imposing restrictions on credit institutions, that is, through capital-based measures.

179
00:29:10,940 --> 00:29:19,940
[SPEAKER_00] The second way, in which the credit cycle can be moderated, is by limiting leverage by households and non-financial corporations.

180
00:29:19,940 --> 00:29:28,940
[SPEAKER_00] With regard to the banking sector, the Capital Requirements Regulation, the CRR, and Directive, the CRRD-4,

181
00:29:29,940 --> 00:29:37,940
[SPEAKER_00] play a prominent role in setting the prudential standards for credit institutions and investment firms in the European Union.

182
00:29:37,940 --> 00:29:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] Implementation is ongoing, and expected to be completed by 2019.

183
00:29:44,940 --> 00:29:53,940
[SPEAKER_00] From January 2016, the counter-cyclical capital buffer, the CCB, the systemic risk buffer, the SRB,

184
00:29:53,940 --> 00:30:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] and the other systemically important institutions, OSII buffer, have been operational.

185
00:30:00,940 --> 00:30:08,940
[SPEAKER_00] Given the need to diversify the available tools beyond regulations based on capital,

186
00:30:09,940 --> 00:30:14,940
[SPEAKER_00] tools based on liquidity, leverage, and funding sources are also being introduced.

187
00:30:14,940 --> 00:30:17,940
[SPEAKER_00] With regard to the borrower side now,

188
00:30:17,940 --> 00:30:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] instruments such as the loan-to-value, the loan-to-income, and debt-service-to-income limits,

189
00:30:24,940 --> 00:30:31,940
[SPEAKER_00] are considered to be among the most effective macroprudential instruments in curtailing excessive credit growth.

190
00:30:31,940 --> 00:30:34,940
[SPEAKER_00] In order to effectively moderate the financial cycle,

191
00:30:35,940 --> 00:30:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] a time-varying dimension is crucial in the design of the various ratios.

192
00:30:40,940 --> 00:30:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] For example, the loan-to-value ratio should be lowered during the expansionary phase of the financial cycle,

193
00:30:49,940 --> 00:30:53,940
[SPEAKER_00] but it should be raised during the contractionary phase.

194
00:30:53,940 --> 00:31:01,940
[SPEAKER_00] Otherwise, there is a risk of pro-cyclicality since leverage constraints decrease as asset prices rise.

195
00:31:02,940 --> 00:31:07,940
[SPEAKER_00] The regulatory initiatives for financial markets and infrastructures,

196
00:31:07,940 --> 00:31:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] and the implementation of the European Market Infrastructure Regulation, the EMIR,

197
00:31:12,940 --> 00:31:16,940
[SPEAKER_00] include macroprudential intervention tools,

198
00:31:16,940 --> 00:31:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] such as enhanced and cooperative oversight framework for central counterparties.

199
00:31:22,940 --> 00:31:31,940
[SPEAKER_00] And thus, indicators that will contribute to better monitoring the extent to which the system is assuming more risks,

200
00:31:31,940 --> 00:31:36,940
[SPEAKER_00] as well as tools which can contribute to maintaining financial stability, are being developed.

201
00:31:37,940 --> 00:31:40,940
[SPEAKER_00] The challenges, of course, remain.

202
00:31:40,940 --> 00:31:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] I will highlight seven of these challenges.

203
00:31:43,940 --> 00:31:48,940
[SPEAKER_00] The first challenge is the completion of the banking union.

204
00:31:48,940 --> 00:31:55,940
[SPEAKER_00] Questions surrounding the financial capacity of the single resolution fund, the SRF,

205
00:31:56,940 --> 00:32:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] both in the short and in the long run, have to be addressed.

206
00:32:00,940 --> 00:32:06,940
[SPEAKER_00] The size of the SRF has been criticized for being insufficient,

207
00:32:06,940 --> 00:32:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] and its governance structure has been criticized as being overly complex.

208
00:32:13,940 --> 00:32:18,940
[SPEAKER_00] If a sound backstop is not in place, there will be pressure for stress tests to become softer,

209
00:32:18,940 --> 00:32:22,940
[SPEAKER_00] which would be a detriment to financial stability.

210
00:32:22,940 --> 00:32:30,940
[SPEAKER_00] DSM could become an effective backstop to the SRF, safeguarding financial stability in the banking union.

211
00:32:31,940 --> 00:32:38,940
[SPEAKER_00] Another issue that requires further reflection concerns the implications of implementing a single

212
00:32:38,940 --> 00:32:42,940
[SPEAKER_00] versus a multiple point of entry in developing resolution plans.

213
00:32:42,940 --> 00:32:45,940
[SPEAKER_00] With respect to deposit insurance,

214
00:32:45,940 --> 00:32:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] aside from the Deposit Guarantee Scheme Directive,

215
00:32:49,940 --> 00:32:53,940
[SPEAKER_00] the transposition of which is still pending in some Member States,

216
00:32:53,940 --> 00:32:58,940
[SPEAKER_00] the proposed European Deposit Insurance Scheme is of paramount importance.

217
00:32:59,940 --> 00:33:05,940
[SPEAKER_00] Deposit Insurance at the supranational level will contribute significantly to financial stability

218
00:33:05,940 --> 00:33:12,940
[SPEAKER_00] by providing a backup when national schemes do not have the capacity to handle large shocks.

219
00:33:12,940 --> 00:33:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] Such insurance will be a decisive step towards breaking the diabolical link between banks and sovereign,

220
00:33:21,940 --> 00:33:28,940
[SPEAKER_00] and along with a sound backstop to the SRF, safeguarding stability across the banking union.

221
00:33:29,940 --> 00:33:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is also important to keep communicating with the markets.

222
00:33:32,940 --> 00:33:43,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, we have to provide consistent communication on regulatory initiatives and macroprudential policies to reduce regulatory uncertainty.

223
00:33:43,940 --> 00:33:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is necessary to revise legislation and EBA guidelines regarding the definition of the minimum distributable amount, the MDA, to bring it into line with other countries.

224
00:33:58,940 --> 00:34:06,940
[SPEAKER_00] We need to harmonize the minimum requirements for own funds and eligible liabilities, that is the MRL, and the Total Loss Absorption Capacity .

225
00:34:06,940 --> 00:34:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] For example, by using the same definition of eligible liabilities for both tools and adjusting the relative thresholds.

226
00:34:16,940 --> 00:34:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] The close cooperation between the SSM and SRF will be needed.

227
00:34:20,940 --> 00:34:26,940
[SPEAKER_00] One first area where this cooperation could be beneficial is at the level of the MRL.

228
00:34:27,940 --> 00:34:38,940
[SPEAKER_00] Finally, we need to promote strategies for banking sector restructuring while having a comprehensive strategy to tackle non-performing loans, the NPLs.

229
00:34:38,940 --> 00:34:44,940
[SPEAKER_00] This is particularly important for banks with high NPL ratios like those in the European South.

230
00:34:45,940 --> 00:34:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] The second challenge ahead relates to the issue of the increased burden of complying with the new regulatory framework and assessing its cumulative impact.

231
00:34:58,940 --> 00:35:01,940
[SPEAKER_00] I am not referring to additional capital adequacy requirements.

232
00:35:01,940 --> 00:35:07,940
[SPEAKER_00] In the pursuit of making banks more robust, liquid, responsible and transparent,

233
00:35:07,940 --> 00:35:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] huge progress to regulate their operation and supervision has been achieved since the crisis erupted in 2008.

234
00:35:16,940 --> 00:35:22,940
[SPEAKER_00] However, there has been no estimate of the cumulative impact of these regulations.

235
00:35:22,940 --> 00:35:28,940
[SPEAKER_00] So, I welcome and look forward to the report on the impact of capital requirements on the economy.

236
00:35:28,940 --> 00:35:33,940
[SPEAKER_00] However, the impact of other regulations should also be examined.

237
00:35:33,940 --> 00:35:38,940
[SPEAKER_00] We need to keep in mind the principle of proportionality.

238
00:35:38,940 --> 00:35:45,940
[SPEAKER_00] As new regulation accumulates, we know that it can come with costs as well as with benefits.

239
00:35:46,940 --> 00:35:56,940
[SPEAKER_00] The policy makers need to be watchful that in attempting to limit externalities, they do not inadvertently create new externalities.

240
00:35:56,940 --> 00:36:03,940
[SPEAKER_00] The financial sector ultimately exists to serve the real economy.

241
00:36:03,940 --> 00:36:11,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is very likely that there are trade-offs between ensuring financial stability and imposing such a burden on the financial sector

242
00:36:12,940 --> 00:36:23,940
[SPEAKER_00] that it ceases to be able to do a job, namely to intermediate between surplus and deficit units in any economy in order to encourage long-term investment and growth.

243
00:36:23,940 --> 00:36:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, we have to develop methods to judge the appropriateness of indicators and tools.

244
00:36:30,940 --> 00:36:46,940
[SPEAKER_00] Since many of the regulations have been applied over the last few years, that is, in a period of acute financial stress, I expect that in the coming years there will be a need to reassess those regulations and perhaps conduct some fine-tuning.

245
00:36:47,940 --> 00:36:54,940
[SPEAKER_00] Similar arguments apply to the national options and discretion in the new regulatory framework.

246
00:36:54,940 --> 00:37:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] Third, closely related to the previous challenge is the degree to which regulatory developments should be front-loaded.

247
00:37:05,940 --> 00:37:16,940
[SPEAKER_00] The regulations themselves often have long phase-in periods such that new versions of the regulations are developed before the previous versions have been fully implemented.

248
00:37:16,940 --> 00:37:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] Supervisors have tended to compensate for the long phase-in periods by front-loading all prudential requirements.

249
00:37:25,940 --> 00:37:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] A situation that sometimes can be considered excessively harsh.

250
00:37:29,940 --> 00:37:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] Of course, the long-facing periods are often a reaction to the expected impact of the regulation on bank behavior and, in particular, on the lending to the real economy.

251
00:37:41,940 --> 00:37:44,940
[SPEAKER_00] Some middle road has to be found.

252
00:37:45,940 --> 00:37:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] A fourth challenge is the need to reduce reliance on models.

253
00:37:49,940 --> 00:37:58,940
[SPEAKER_00] Recently conducted stress tests at the European Union level followed a so-called single-model-fits-all methodology,

254
00:37:58,940 --> 00:38:04,940
[SPEAKER_00] which left very little room for idiosyncratic and specific national characteristics.

255
00:38:04,940 --> 00:38:13,940
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, according to some analysts, there is a risk that stress tests are becoming less effective as a supervisory tool.

256
00:38:14,940 --> 00:38:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] Instead, they may increasingly be seen as having been undertaken in order to calm the markets.

257
00:38:20,940 --> 00:38:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] Ideally, stress tests should be implemented in benign times in accordance with an old wisdom attributed to John Fitzgerald Kennedy

258
00:38:32,940 --> 00:38:37,940
[SPEAKER_00] that the time to repair the roof is when the sun is shining.

259
00:38:38,940 --> 00:38:51,940
[SPEAKER_00] In crisis times, there is the risk that crucial inputs such as macroeconomic variables are under or overestimated and that adverse scenarios become unrealistic, either too benign or too severe.

260
00:38:51,940 --> 00:38:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] In consequence, there are ambiguous outcomes that are difficult to interpret.

261
00:38:58,940 --> 00:38:59,940
[SPEAKER_00] For example, stress tests should be improved.

262
00:38:59,940 --> 00:39:14,940
[SPEAKER_00] More appropriately, stress tests should not only place emphasis on solvency, but they should explode the impact of the assumed shock on bank liquidity,

263
00:39:14,940 --> 00:39:22,940
[SPEAKER_00] the implications of applying the bail-in tool, the funds needed to meet any demand on deposit guarantee funds, etc.

264
00:39:23,940 --> 00:39:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] We should focus on harmonizing processes while models should be enriched with constrained judgment as a standard practice in macroeconomic forecasting.

265
00:39:33,940 --> 00:39:36,940
[SPEAKER_00] For example, there is a need to widen the scope of regulation.

266
00:39:36,940 --> 00:39:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] A crucial challenge ahead is related to recent disintermediation and the development of shadow banking as an alternative means of financial intermediation.

267
00:39:50,940 --> 00:40:02,940
[SPEAKER_00] The CRR/CRD4 legal framework covers mainly the banking sector, yet financial stability and the financing of the euro-area economy have increasingly shifted to non-banks.

268
00:40:02,940 --> 00:40:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] The need for macro-prudential regulation of certain financial activities becomes clear if we consider that banks and non-banks are closely tied through market-based intermediation activities.

269
00:40:16,940 --> 00:40:27,940
[SPEAKER_00] This includes a broad area of services related to securitization transactions, securities financing transactions, repos, collateral management and derivatives.

270
00:40:27,940 --> 00:40:38,940
[SPEAKER_00] The consequences of poorly monitored risks in this area are unknown, and the risk of a new crisis could be lurking, while spillover effects are difficult to assess.

271
00:40:39,940 --> 00:40:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, the more that policymakers are effective in using macro-prudential tools to constrain excessive credit growth in the banking sector, the more likely it becomes that there will be excessive adjustments in the non-bank sector through leakages.

272
00:40:58,940 --> 00:41:06,940
[SPEAKER_00] Unfortunately, shadow banking is high on the agenda of the relevant fora, and there is a clear need to extend the regulatory toolkit.

273
00:41:06,940 --> 00:41:10,940
[SPEAKER_00] At this point, I would like to mention also the Capital Markets Union.

274
00:41:10,940 --> 00:41:20,940
[SPEAKER_00] The Capital Markets Union aims at connecting saving more effectively to investment, by funding projects in a transparent and ordered way.

275
00:41:21,940 --> 00:41:30,940
[SPEAKER_00] In this way, it could contribute to growth by providing alternatives to traditional bank intermediation for savers and investors.

276
00:41:30,940 --> 00:41:44,940
[SPEAKER_00] In pursuit of growth, Europe needs a financial system that is able to meet the financing needs of all economic entities, that is businesses and households, at different stages in their development.

277
00:41:45,940 --> 00:41:58,940
[SPEAKER_00] Finally, a sixth challenge is one that the SSM has identified as a top priority for its supervisory action plan for 2016, namely, banks' business model and profitability.

278
00:41:58,940 --> 00:42:07,940
[SPEAKER_00] In particular, low profitability in a low, even negative interest rate landscape is a key challenge that banks need to address.

279
00:42:08,940 --> 00:42:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] Moreover, European banks have to address the problem of radical restructuring, which has been delayed in many cases.

280
00:42:15,940 --> 00:42:24,940
[SPEAKER_00] This observation, accompanied by frequent top management changes, stands in contrast to strategy implementation in the United States.

281
00:42:24,940 --> 00:42:32,940
[SPEAKER_00] It is even more complicated now, with the deterioration in market sentiment and the weaker-than-expected economic outlook.

282
00:42:33,940 --> 00:42:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] Part of the challenge in addressing a new business model relates to the increasing stock of non-performing exposures and their management.

283
00:42:41,940 --> 00:42:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] These exposures are acting as a significant impediment to banks re-orienting their business model, as well as, more broadly, to growth and financial stability, particularly in the countries of the European South.

284
00:42:58,940 --> 00:43:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] It should be highlighted, however, that we are not in a good position to deal with this challenging issue, as thanks to the comprehensive assessment and the asset quality review,

285
00:43:09,940 --> 00:43:18,940
[SPEAKER_00] we are now fully aware of the full picture and important knowledge has been acquired for both monitoring and managing troubled assets.

286
00:43:19,940 --> 00:43:29,940
[SPEAKER_00] At the Bank of Greece, our research on the issue of NPLs indicate that they are overwhelmingly driven by recession.

287
00:43:29,940 --> 00:43:34,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, additional capital requirements cannot always provide a remedy.

288
00:43:35,940 --> 00:43:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] Indeed, in some cases, such a remedy is likely to prove suboptimal.

289
00:43:41,940 --> 00:43:47,940
[SPEAKER_00] Instead, at the Bank of Greece, we have concluded that active private sector loan restructuring,

290
00:43:47,940 --> 00:43:50,940
[SPEAKER_00] the improvement in the insolvency framework,

291
00:43:50,940 --> 00:44:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] more efficient judicial systems and the involvement of loan services and private equity funds with experience in restructuring sectors of the economy,

292
00:44:00,940 --> 00:44:05,940
[SPEAKER_00] are crucial components of an overall strategy of dealing with NPLs.

293
00:44:05,940 --> 00:44:15,940
[SPEAKER_00] The role of central banks as a lender of last resort to the banking system needs also to be addressed,

294
00:44:15,940 --> 00:44:21,940
[SPEAKER_00] on the basis of principles that are consistent with our mandate of preserving financial stability.

295
00:44:22,940 --> 00:44:27,940
[SPEAKER_00] The principle developed by Thornton and Baggahot is well known.

296
00:44:27,940 --> 00:44:35,940
[SPEAKER_00] Central banks should lend freely to solvent but illiquid banks against good collateral at a high rate of interest.

297
00:44:35,940 --> 00:44:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] How is this tried and tested principle to be made operational in today's environment,

298
00:44:41,940 --> 00:44:46,940
[SPEAKER_00] with much larger bank balance sheets and fewer liquid assets?

299
00:44:47,940 --> 00:44:53,940
[SPEAKER_00] In the past, government bonds were automatically considered as good collateral.

300
00:44:53,940 --> 00:44:57,940
[SPEAKER_00] Today, central banks accept a wider pool of collateral.

301
00:44:57,940 --> 00:45:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] By what criteria should collateral be judged?

302
00:45:00,940 --> 00:45:09,940
[SPEAKER_00] We know that liquidity problems can become solvency problems if liquidity is denied or not provided generously enough.

303
00:45:10,940 --> 00:45:18,940
[SPEAKER_00] Thus, the seemingly simple principle developed by Thornton and Baggahot can be open to various interpretations.

304
00:45:18,940 --> 00:45:22,940
[SPEAKER_00] There is a need, I think, to revisit the question.

305
00:45:23,940 --> 00:45:31,940
[SPEAKER_00] Mervie King's pawnbroker concept in his recent book provides some new ideas on this issue.

306
00:45:31,940 --> 00:45:41,940
[SPEAKER_00] The ultimate aim in meeting these challenges is to make financing Europe more resilient and to enhance and safeguard financial stability.

307
00:45:41,940 --> 00:45:48,940
[SPEAKER_00] The role of supervisors of the financial system is to enhance harmonization while respecting proportionality.

308
00:45:49,940 --> 00:46:00,940
[SPEAKER_00] They should safeguard a level playing field among all participants and protect depositors while striking the right balance between strictness and fairness.

309
00:46:00,940 --> 00:46:11,940
[SPEAKER_00] Their mandate is to set clear boundaries within which financial intermediation can prosper while financial stability is maintained.

310
00:46:12,940 --> 00:46:16,940
[SPEAKER_00] The financial sector is facing challenges on many fronts.

311
00:46:16,940 --> 00:46:18,940
[SPEAKER_00] Banks are no exception.

312
00:46:18,940 --> 00:46:33,940
[SPEAKER_00] Jonathan Hill recently spoke about a brave new world for banks and the need of a revolution in which banks are reformed and restructured with respect to both their business models and governance.

313
00:46:33,940 --> 00:46:37,940
[SPEAKER_00] Supervisors will also have to adapt to this revolution.

314
00:46:38,940 --> 00:46:44,940
[SPEAKER_00] The economic and monetary union in the past few years with banking union as the flagship of the reform effort.

315
00:46:44,940 --> 00:46:49,940
[SPEAKER_00] More progress is needed as EMU remains incomplete.

316
00:46:49,940 --> 00:46:52,940
[SPEAKER_00] Economic and monetary union remains incomplete.

317
